         <abstract>
            <p>One-period capital budgeting models employed in financial decision making do not provide for a complete allocation of expected returns. There exists an "owner's surplus," not considered in traditional models. The existence of this surplus vitiates normative entrepreneurial theory, and implies problems in equilibrium adjustment for capital budgeting algorithms.</p>
